english:
  title: A Letter Summoning Zhao Zhang
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Commander-in-Chief sends this letter to Zhao Zhang.

    The ancients once said: "When a great mansion is completed, the swallows come to congratulate. When the bath is filled, the lice gather to mourn." Consider well the difference between their congratulations and their sorrows—both arise from whether they have a place to depend upon or not.

    You have joined with the wicked in rebellion, daring to maintain this treachery as though it were permanent. But I have marshaled both navy and army, and Heaven and men support what is right. Long have I studied the meeting of wind and cloud; far have I displayed the majesty of thunder and lightning. Soon I shall unfold my strategies and swiftly capture the rebel leader, recover the cities, and still the dust and smoke.

    You understand my intentions well enough. Know this: spring comes before autumn—such is Heaven's way. Rewards are valued above punishments—such is the sovereign's grace. Therefore do I send this humble letter to inquire into your heart's true condition.

    You cling to the chief of traitors and disturb the court. Your crimes are overflowing, and by reason they should be cut away. Yet if one such as Huang Chao could transform his savage nature and renew himself with noble intent, desiring to be enfeoffed as a marquis and have his house and altar established, then his deeds would surpass all ages past and present, and his honors would pass to his descendants. This shall surely come to pass—respond swiftly.

    But if you raise your arms in defiance like the mantis, gnashing teeth like the fierce beast, then I shall certainly destroy you utterly. You must examine carefully the ultimate principle and persuade the chief conspirator. Let all under Heaven know your name and display your loyalty early. Do not skulk in the grass seeking mere survival, only to become a rebel at last.

    Consider: the calculation is already made; the nest will soon be overturned. Life and death have their mandate; fortune and misfortune have no separate gate. Only by discerning right from wrong can success and failure be known. Whether the swallows congratulate or the lice mourn depends truly upon knowing or not knowing, upon following or not following what is right. Good fortune is easily lost; noble opportunity is hard to find. To live as one who causes harm, to die as an unknowing ghost—this is deeply shameful, deeply lamentable.

    Consider well your choice and come quickly to heel. Understand this.
  footnotes:
    - Huang Chao (黃巢) was a prominent rebel leader during the late Tang dynasty, known for his eventual surrender and subsequent employment by the court.
    - The imagery of swallows congratulating and lice mourning refers to the dependence of lesser beings on circumstances—a metaphor for those who follow power and circumstance rather than principle.
    - This letter appears to be addressed to a subordinate commander wavering in loyalty during a period of political instability in Korea.
